    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a really strong start for the lesson. Some of my students are a bit confused though, because they've heard the term \"procedural due process\" mentioned in other contexts. How should I explain the difference so they understand why the substantive side is the one that actually protects those big personal liberties?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Procedural due process is about *how* the government acts—it demands fair procedures like proper notice and a chance to be heard before you are penalized. Substantive due process, however, is about *what* the government is allowed to do in the first place, protecting core rights even if the procedures are technically followed. Think of it this way: procedural due process is the rulebook for the game, while substantive due process defines the fundamental, unchangeable rules of the game itself.",
      "source": "target",
