      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That critique is a common, but ultimately flawed, argument used by those who fear judicial power. The idea that judges \"make up laws\" ignores the deep historical roots of these rights in the nation's founding principles and evolving understanding of liberty. When the Supreme Court upholds substantive due process, it is not inventing rights; it is enforcing the inherent moral and constitutional protections that the system is designed to safeguard against tyranny.",
      "source": "target",
